Thus, even grammar and pronunciation—such as the use of subcultural dialects (black English, accented English) and nondominant languages—vary by microcontext, as many creative field experiments have shown (see, e.g., essays on code switching collected in Gumperz and Hymes [1972], Gumperz [1982a
                     ,1982b
                     ], Gigliolo [1972]). People know the rules of grammar and pronunciation, but do not always use them; and their code‐switching varies in statistically regular patterns.
